Language: en

00:00:00.530 --> 00:00:02.180
What we're going to do in
this video is think

00:00:02.180 --> 00:00:04.660
about two wave sources.

00:00:04.660 --> 00:00:08.890
But one of them is going to be
stationary and the other one

00:00:08.890 --> 00:00:10.000
is going to be moving.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:12.890
And just to have a concrete
number, it's moving at 5

00:00:12.890 --> 00:00:15.570
meters per second
to the right.

00:00:15.570 --> 00:00:18.960
And what we're going to think
about is where are the crests

00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:21.280
of the wave that it's
been releasing for

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.340
the last 3 or 4 seconds?

00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:26.565
So let's say that in both cases,
they are releasing a

00:00:26.565 --> 00:00:30.860
wave. So the velocity of the
wave is going to be 10 meters

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:31.450
per second.

00:00:31.450 --> 00:00:34.420
You could visualize this, maybe,
as a sound wave, but

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:37.120
sound and air move much, much,
much, much faster than 10

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.050
meters per second.

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:39.890
But this'll make the
math work out easy.

00:00:39.890 --> 00:00:42.040
Especially relative to this
guy, who is moving to the

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:44.220
right at 5 meters per second.

00:00:44.220 --> 00:00:45.760
And that's the whole point, to
give you the intuition and

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:47.330
make the math really
simple here.

00:00:47.330 --> 00:00:50.400
And both of these guys are going
to be, the wave that

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:52.040
they're emitting is at
10 meters per second.

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:54.110
And the period of the wave
is going to be at

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:57.370
1 second per cycle.

00:00:57.370 --> 00:00:59.940
And if the period is 1 second
per cycle, you take the

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:04.430
inverse of that-- the frequency
of the source, I

00:01:04.430 --> 00:01:07.570
guess you could call it, of the
wave, as being emitted is

00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:08.710
going to be the inverse
of this.

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:10.100
The inverse of 1 is just 1.

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:14.680
But 1 cycle per second.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:17.910
If it takes a second for a
cycle, it's also in 1 second,

00:01:17.910 --> 00:01:21.180
you're also going to see 1
cycle, so 1 cycle per second.

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:23.740
So let's think about what's
happening here.

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:27.250
So let's think about where--
let's say it emitted a crest

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:29.810
of it's a wave exactly
1 second ago.

00:01:29.810 --> 00:01:31.570
Where is that crest
going to be now?

00:01:31.570 --> 00:01:33.750
Let's think about the stationary
character.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.630
Well, this guy emitted
a crest 1 second ago.

00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:37.850
It's moving outward.

00:01:37.850 --> 00:01:38.760
So this is outward.

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.710
It's movie outward radially.

00:01:40.710 --> 00:01:43.660
We need to give a direction if
I'm giving a vector quantity.

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:45.410
So it's moving outward at
10 meters per second.

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:48.260
So if it emitted it 1 second
ago, it's going to be 10

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:50.480
meters radially outward
from the source.

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:56.380
So maybe that is right
over there.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:01:58.090
Well, let me draw it a little
bit neater like that.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:05.880
So that's where that
crest will be.

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:06.730
Now what about this guy?

00:02:06.730 --> 00:02:10.940
Where's the crest that this
guy emitted 1 second ago?

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:13.960
You might want to just draw a
radius 10 meters around this

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:14.460
